965 and the passenger station and freight depot was bought by [[Madison Gas and Electric]] (MGE) and has been renovated to serve as offices. The station and freight depot are listed as contributing properties on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] [[East Wilson Street Historic District]]. The [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad]] (commonly known as the Milwaukee Road) had tracks paralleling the C&NW and also had a nearby passenger station.\n\n==History==\n===Early depots===\nThe first railroad entering Madison was the Milwaukee and Mississippi Railroad, a predecessor of the Milwaukee Road. Their depot was established on the west side of Madison in 1854.<ref name=\"West\">{{cite web|title=West Madison Depot, Chicago, Milwaukee, and St. Paul Railway|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|date=February 1981|location=[[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]]|first1=Lance|last1=Neckar|first2=Katharine H.|last2=Rankin|url={{NRHP url|id=85000990}}|accessdate=April 8, 2020|work=[[NRHP]] Inventory-Nomination Form}}</ref> The Chicago and North Western constructed a line to Madison in 1864 from the south, crossing [[Lake Monona|Monona Bay]]. The first passenger station on the site was established in 1871.<ref>{{cite book|title=Madison|first=David|last=Sakrison|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZA9QnQHB2pMC|date=2009|accessdate=April 10, 2020|ISBN=0738560545|page=58\u201359}}</ref> Due to the proximity of the Milwaukee Road, the C&NW originally wanted to construct an [[union station]] in the area. The Milwaukee Road declined and built their own depot.<ref name=\"NRHP\">{{cite web|first=Katherine H.|last=Rankin|work=NRHP Inventory-Nomination Form|date=October 15, 1985|accessdate=April 10, 2020|publisher=National Parks Service|url={{NRHP url|id=86000618}}|title=East Wilson Street Historic District|location=Madison}}</ref><ref name=\"Formative\">{{cite book|title=Madison, a History of the Formative Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NwrIKM0rBd4C|first=David V.|last=Mollenhoff|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin]] Press|location=Madison|date=2003|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|124}}\n\nMadison eventually became a junction point for the Chicago and North Western, as lines were completed north to [[Baraboo, Wisconsin|Baraboo]] and [[Minneapolis]]. Other lines to [[Lancaster, Wisconsin|Lancaster]] and [[Milwaukee]] were completed in the early 1800s. A new station was completed in the same location in 1885, and included a hotel and dining room within the structure.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/>\n\n===Current depot===\nAfter the opening of a new Milwaukee Road [[Milwaukee Road Depot (Madison, Wisconsin)|depot]] in West Madison, the C&NW made plans for a new larger station, costing [[USD|$]]500,000. Leaders in the government of Madison were in support of the plan, but nearby business owners and residents objected. These objections were due to the plan that would close the [[level crossing|crossing]] of Blount Street to allow for expanded [[railroad platform|platforms]]. A series of legal proceedings ending up costing 10 years before the C&NW revised plans.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/><ref name=\"Formative\"/>{{rp|263}}\n\nThe scaled-down station opened in 1910, at a cost of $250,000, and the Blount Street crossing remains open to this day.<ref>{{cite web|title=289 S Blount St|website=[[Google Maps]]|publisher=[[Google]]|url=https://goo.gl/maps/56QQFCR87FDRDb9QA|date=August 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> A freight depot was also built [[circa|c.]] 1908, just northwest of the station.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/> The new station was a success, and was described in 1915 as a \"bustling, buzzing, exciting hub of activity.\"<ref name=\"NRHP\"/>  The station served local and named passenger trains, such as the ''Duluth\u2013Superior Limited'', ''The Mountaineer'', and the ''The Viking.''<ref name=\"Classic\">{{cite magazine|url=https://ctr.trains.com/way-it-was/railfan-stories/2016/09/remembering-the-cnw-in-madison|magazine=Classic Trains|publication-date=Fall 2009|date=September 6, 2016|first=Frank|last=Rogers|accessdate=April 11, 2020|title=Remembering the C&NW in Madison}}</ref> With the introduction of [[streamliner]] trains, Madison was served by the ''[[Minnesota 400]]'', later renamed the ''Dakota 400'' and ''Rochester 400''. The ''[[Twin Cities 400]]'' from Chicago\u2013Minneapolis used the faster line through Milwaukee, with a connection to the ''Minnesota 400'' at [[Wyeville, Wisconsin|Wyeville]].<ref>{{cite|title=Chicago and North Western System|section=Chicago To Madison|page=22|publisher=[[Chicago and North Western Railway]]|date=October 30, 1955}}</ref><ref name=\"Journal\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Passenger Train Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412190057/https://dvqlxo2m2q99q.cloudfront.net/000_clients/1279252/file/ptj2.pdf|archive-date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020|url=https://dvqlxo2m2q99q.cloudfront.net/000_clients/1279252/file/ptj2.pdf|title=Wisconsin DOT and Amtrak: Heading for Madison?|first=Stephen|last=Karlson|date=April 2009|issue=154|url-status=live}}</ref> The station was also used for special trains for [[Wisconsin Badgers football|University of Wisconsin football]] games.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/>\n\nIntercity passenger trains in the United States declined after [[World War II]], with fierce competition from the automobile and airplanes. The ''Rochester 400'' made its last run on July 23, 1963.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Post-Bulletin]]|location=[[Rochester, Minnesota|Rochester]]|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/news/local/day-in-history-the-rochester-makes-its-last-run-today/article_492190d5-ed94-5160-b3d4-046c07c19de9.html|date=July 23, 2013|accessdate=April 12, 2020|title=Day in History: The Rochester \u201c400\u201d makes its last run today|author=<!--No author listed-->}}</ref> This left Madison with only one C&NW operated train\u2014an unnamed local train to Chicago.<ref>{{cite|title=Through Passenger Train Schedules|publisher=Chicago and North Western Railway|section=Chicago\u2013Madison|page=5|date=June 22, 1964}}</ref> This too was discontinued on June 21, 1965. [[Madison Gas and Electric]] (MGE) bought the passenger and freight station later that month for $390,000.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Madison_in_the_Sixties.html?id=M5B8DwAAQBAJ&source=kp_book_description|title=Madison in the Sixties|publisher=[[Wisconsin Historical Society]]|date=November 19, 2018|accessdate=April 10, 2020|first=Stuart D.|last=Levitan|ISBN=0870208845}}</ref> MGE moved their main offices to the complex in 1983, and renovated the interior, while keeping the exterior [[facade]] of the passenger station.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/> The surrounding [[East Wilson Street Historic District|area]] was listed as a [[Historic districts in the United States|historic district]] in 1986, and the property was listed on the Wisconsin State Register of Historic Places in 1989.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=133 S Blair St|website=Wisconsin Historical Society|accessdate=April 11, 2020|url=https://www.wisconsinhistory.org/Records/Property/HI79532}}</ref> \n\n==Site description==\nThe 1910 station was built as a partial [[railroad terminal|stub end terminal]], with two [[through track]]s connecting to the west. This configuration allowed for separate tracks that would be terminating at Madison, and avoided congestion.<ref name=\"Classic\"/> However, the [[Madison, Wisconsin#Geography|geography of Madison]] still required trains from Milwaukee to perform a backup move in order to access the northern line to Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Journal\"/> The structure was designed by the firm [[Frost & Granger]], who was notable for designing other railroad buildings such as the [[Chicago and North Western Terminal]] in Chicago. The two-story [[neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] structure was made from [[Bedford stone]] and was designed to be similar to the Chicago terminal.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/>\n\nThe nearby freight depot was built on the corner of Blair and Railroad Streets. It is two stories tall and made from red brick, with large rounded windows. A [[Railway roundhouse|roundhouse]] was also built to the east of the station, and became notable with a boiler of a steam engine exploded in 1898.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicmadison.org/Madison's%20Past/connectingwithourpast/railroadstations.html|title=Railroad Stations|accessdate=April 10, 2020|website=Historic Madison, Inc. of Wisconsin|location=Madison}}</ref> The two tracks of the C&NW intersected a single track of the Milwaukee Road with an unique [[diamond crossing]] within a grade crossing of Blair Street.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/> Only one track currently remains, and is operated by the [[Wisconsin and Southern Railroad]].<ref>{{cite map|title=Wisconsin Railroads & Harbors 2020|author=[[Wisconsin Department of Transportation]]|date=January 2020|url=https://wisconsindot.gov/Documents/travel/rail/railmap.pdf|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Milwaukee Road Station==\nThe '''Franklin Street station''', also known as '''East Madison station''', was a [[Milwaukee Road]] station. It was located at 501 East Wilson Street, one [[city block|block]] west from the C&NW station. The first station on the site was built in 1869.<ref name=\"West\"/><ref name=\"Formative\"/>{{rp|124}} This was replaced with a 1886 structure in a [[Victorian Gothic]] style, in order to compete with the new C&NW station.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/> It served trains from Madison to [[Portage, Wisconsin|Portage]] and [[Milwaukee]], including the ''On Wisconsin''.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Official Guide of the Railways]]|date=June 1941|publisher=National Railways Publishing Company|location=[[New York City]]|page=964|section=[[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad]]}}</ref> The station was demolished in 1952, and all Milwaukee Road passenger service shifted to the still-standing [[Milwaukee Road Depot (Madison, Wisconsin)|West Madison]] station.<ref name=\"NRHP\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200 px>\nFile:Madison C&NW station freight depot 1.jpg|The freight depot, northwest of the station in 2020.\nFile:Madison C&NW 2.jpg|Postcard of station from the 1910s.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n{{Commons category|Madison (C&NW station)}}\n*[http://www.trainweb.org/rshs/VRP%20Madison%20CNW%20Pt1.htm Madison, Wisconsin Vintage Rail Photos \u2013 TrainWeb (Part 1)]\n*[http://www.trainweb.org/rshs/VRP%20Madison%20CNW%20Pt2.htm Madison, Wisconsin Vintage Rail Photos \u2013 TrainWeb (Part 2)]\n\n[[Category:Railway stations on the National Register of Historic Places in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Former Chicago and North Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1910]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1871]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1885]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1965]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Charles Sumner Frost buildings]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Former railway stations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "RFD", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madison_station_(C%26NW)"}
